  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "To use them despitefully.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The verb expresses wanton insult and outrage. St. Paul uses the noun derived from it to express the character of his own conduct as a persecutor (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Timothy 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and must have felt, as afterwards in the actual stoning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that he was receiving the just reward of his own deeds.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 14:5-7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 14:5-7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when there was an assault made ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Or was about to be made; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "both of the Gentiles, and the Jews ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who, though generally at enmity with one another, yet were united against the Christians, as Herod and Pontius Pilate, the Pharisees and Sadducees, against Christ. If the churches enemies can unite for its destruction, shall not its friends, laying aside all personal feuds, unite for its preservation? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To use them despitefully",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — To expose them to disgrace; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "then to stone, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and put them to death: and thus they hoped to ruin their cause. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They were aware of it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— When the project was just ripe for execution, Paul and Barnabas received intelligence of it, and prevented the bloody attempt by withdrawing from thence; they ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fled unto Lystra ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "first, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "then to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Derbe; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and after that to the region that lay round Lycaonia, namely, the region of Phrygia and Galatia. In thus fleeing from their persecutors they followed their Master’s advice, who directed them, when persecuted in one city, to flee unto another: for though he enabled them to work miracles for the confirmation of the gospel, he gave them no power of working any to save themselves from persecution. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And there they preached ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Κακει ησαν ευαγγελιζομενοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and there they were preaching; the gospel ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And that, it appears, in a very successful manner, so that the church was still increased by the very methods taken to destroy it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14:1-7 The apostles spake so plainly, with such evidence and proof of the Spirit, and with such power; so warmly, and with such concern for the souls of men; that those who heard them could not but say, God was with them of a truth. Yet the success was not to be reckoned to the manner of their preaching, but to the Spirit of God who used that means. Perseverance in doing good, amidst dangers and hardships, is a blessed evidence of grace. Wherever God's servants are driven, they should seek to declare the truth. When they went on in Christ's name and strength, he failed not to give testimony to the word of his grace. He has assured us it is the word of God, and that we may venture our souls upon it. The Gentiles and Jews were at enmity with one another, yet united against Christians. If the church's enemies join to destroy it, shall not its friends unite for its preservation? God has a shelter for his people in a storm; he is, and will be their Hiding-place. In times of persecution, believers may see cause to quit a spot, though they do not quit their Master's work.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "An assault made - Greek: a \"rush\" - ὁρμή  hormē. It denotes \"an impetuous excitement and aggression; a rush to put them to death.\" It rather describes a popular tumult than a calm and deliberate purpose. There was a violent, tumultuous excitement.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Both of the Gentiles ... - Of that part of them which was opposed to the apostles.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To use them despitefully - See the notes on Matthew 5:44. To reproach them; to bring contempt upon them; to injure them.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "To use them despitefully - See the notes on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 5:44",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". To reproach them; to bring contempt upon them; to injure them.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And to stone them - To put them to death by stoning; probably as blasphemers, Acts 7:57-59. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And to stone them - To put them to death by stoning; probably as blasphemers, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 7:57-59",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "5. an assault made … to stone them—rather here, \"an impetuous movement\" with a view to stoning them: for in 2Co 11:25, Paul says, \"Once I was stoned,\" and that was at Lystra, as expressly related in Ac 14:19. (Paley's remarks—Horæ Paulinæ—on this singular coincidence between the Epistle and the history are very striking).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "fled—(See Mt 10:23).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
