  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The real contrast is marked in this verse, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὡς δὲ ἐγέν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Hitherto the evil results indicated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " had not resulted in an open combination of Jews and Gentiles to injure Paul and Barnabas, but now the Jews and their rulers were prepared to act in concert with the Gentiles, so that the opposition assumed a public shape, and a definite accusation of blasphemy could be formulated against the Apostles.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁρμὴ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “onset,” R.V.; “assault,” A.V., but neither word seems appropriate, since neither onset nor assault actually occurred. It seems therefore better to take the word as expressing the inclination, or hostile intention, or instigation, and to connect it with the infinitives. In classical Greek the word is used of eagerness (joined with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπιθυμία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of impulse, of eager desire of, or for, a thing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Thuc. iv. 4, Plat., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Phil.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 35 D, although it is also used of an assault or attack. The only other place in the N.T. in which it occurs is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jam 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (R.V. renders “impulse”). Hesychius regards it as equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "βουλή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπιθυμία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " but see also for its use as expressing attack, violence, 3Ma 1:16; 3Ma 1:23; 3Ma 4:5.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σὺν τοῖς ἄρχουσιν αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of the Jewish synagogues, as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " shows. Hackett and Lumby take it of the heathen magistrates. On the distinction between these and the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀρχισυνάγωγος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see Schürer, div. ii., vol. ii., pp. 64, 250, E.T. The magistrates of the city could not have participated in an act of mob-violence, and the plot to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stone",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Apostles seems to point to Jewish instigation for enforcing the punishment of blasphemy.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑβρίσαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “to entreat them shamefully,” so A. and R.V., indicating outrage, insolence in act, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 22:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 18:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Ma 14:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 3Ma 6:9; in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 11:45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of insulting words. St. Paul uses the same word of treatment at Philippi, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and he describes his own conduct towards the Christians by the cognate noun ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑβριστής",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when there was an assault made",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The noun does not necessarily imply that any direct attack had been made, which, from what follows, we can see was not the case. It rather applies to the excitement, urging, and instigation which the Jews were applying to their heathen companions, and which was likely to end in violence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "with their rulers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The word is of the most general character, and it is impossible to form any conjecture from it what these authorities ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "were",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and to stone them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] From this we see that the prompting came from the Jews. Stoning was their mode of punishment for blasphemy, and such they would represent the teaching of the Apostles to be. We need not suppose that any regular legal stoning like that of Stephen was intended, or that to accomplish that object the rulers here mentioned were such Jewish authorities as could be gathered together in Iconium, and that they are indicated by a vague term because they had no very settled position. The previous verb “to use them despitefully” rather points to the opposite conclusion, and marks the intended proceeding as a piece of mob-outrage, for which the countenance of any authority was gladly welcomed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In connection with St Paul’s residence at Iconium, there exists a story of the conversion of a maiden named Thecla, of which the apocryphal “Acts of Paul and Thecla” represents the form into which the legend had grown in the fourth century. Thecla, who was espoused to Thamyris, is said to have been deeply affected by the preaching of the Apostle, which she accidentally heard, and when the Apostle was put in prison on the accusation of being a magician, she bribed the gaoler and visited the prisoner, and was fully instructed by him in the Christian faith. The Apostle was punished and sent away from Iconium. Thecla was condemned to die for her refusal to marry Thamyris, but was miraculously saved, and after many troubles joined St Paul in his missionary travels, and ultimately made her home in the neighbourhood of Seleucia, where she led the life of a nun till her death, which took place when she was ninety years old.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This story may at first have had some basis of truth to rest on, but it has been so distorted with inconsistent details, that it is impossible now to judge what the foundation of it may have been.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Made an onset",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "an assault made",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of the Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "also of the Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "entreat them shamefully",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for to use ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "them despitefully",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V., as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As regards ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὁρμή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", neither the A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "assault",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " nor the R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "onset",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " expresses it exactly. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Ὁρμή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " means the strong bent of the mind, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "James 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it expresses the strong will of the steersman directing the ship against the force of the winds. Here it means that both Jews with their rulers, and Gentiles, under the influence of violent passion, had determined and agreed to assault Paul and Barnabas. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To entreat them shamefully",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Ψβρις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὑβρίζω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " denote \"violence,\" as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 22:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 18:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 12:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is sometimes used of corporal punish-merit, even legally inflicted, as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (LXX.). Acts 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
